[[ja:%E5%85%AB%E5%9D%82%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE (%E7%B7%B4%E9%A6%AC%E5%8C%BA%E5%A4%A7%E6%B3%89%E7%94%BA)]]

{{infobox religious building | name = Yasaka Shrine (Oizumi-cho, Honma District) | native_name = [[:en:Yasaka Shrine|Yasaka Shrine]] | religious_affiliation = [[:en:Shinto|Shinto]] | image = [[File:Yasaka Jinja Nerima.jpg|300px]] | image description = Main Hall of Yasaka Shrine (Oizumi-cho, Honma District) | location = [[:en:Tokyo|Tokyo Metropolis]] [[:en:Nerima|Nerima Ward]] [[:en:Ōizumi, Gunma|Oizumi-cho]] | address = 1-44-1, Oizumi-cho | deity = {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔嗚命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}} | temple_Ranking = (if any; here given as "Village Shrine") | founded = | subsidiary shrines = [[:en:Inari shrine|Inari Shrine]], [[:en:Sengen shrine|Asama Shrine]], {{ill|Mikudate Shrine|ja|御嶽神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikudate Shrine|qq=}} | alternate name = | festival = Main festival (example: Grand Festival around June 15) | coordinates = {{ウィキ座標2段度分秒|35|46|2|N|139|36|22|E}} }} '''Yasaka Shrine''' ([[:en:Yasaka Shrine|Yasaka Shrine]]) in Oizumi-cho, Honma District is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto Shrine]] located in Oizumi-cho, Nerima Ward, Tokyo. It is a village shrine and is famed for legends concerning a curse for those who eat melons, due to its association with the “Gion” tradition. == Deity == The primary deity is {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|素戔嗚命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}. In addition, three subsidiary deities enshrined in the subsidiary shrines are: * {{ill|Ukano Mitama|ja|稲蒼魂命|1=Ukanomitama|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukano Mitama|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukanomitama|qq=}} (at the Inari Shrine) * {{ill|Konohana Sakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohana Sakuya-hime|13=User:Immanuelle/Konohanasakuya-hime|qq=}} (at the Asama Shrine) * {{ill|Kunitsukuri-no-mikoto|ja|国常立命|1=Kuni-no-Tokotachi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunitsukuri-no-mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni-no-Tokotachi|qq=}} (at the Mikudate Shrine) == History == Its founding date is unknown. The {{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō|ja|新編武蔵国風土記稿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō|qq=}} also records that “the history of the shrine’s establishment is unknown” (see also {{sfn|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki-kō, Hashido Village, Tennōsha}}). In that text it is also referred to as “Tennōsha.” The name was changed to Yasaka Shrine in the early Meiji period due to the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離令|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Bunri|qq=}}. == Grounds == An image of a “Fujizuka” (a mound resembling Mt. Fuji) known as “Nakazato Fuji” stands on the right-hand side of the shrine’s main hall. This mound was constructed by the local 【ill|Fuji-kō|ja|富士講】 group from the Edo period to early Showa period. A stone monument dated to 1822 ([[:en:Bunsei|Bunsei]] 5) within the mound suggests that its construction began in the Edo period and was later completed in the early Meiji period by the local {{ill|Marukichi-kō|ja|丸吉講|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Marukichi-kō|qq=}}. Local traditional events are still celebrated by the descendants of the Fuji-kō. Inside the ema hall, several votive plaques and pilgrimage pictures (ema) dating from the Edo period display realistic depictions of the shrine’s historical scenery. == Festivals and Annual Events == * The main festival is held around June 15 (example: “Reidai-sai”) * Other annual events include Bon Odori in July, and a “Yamate no Fuji” opening event in August – the largest mound in the district, which has been designated as a tangible folk cultural property. * The “Nakazato Hayashi,” a traditional festival inherited from the Edo period, is still performed during the New Year at the shrine. == Cultural Properties == === Tangible Folk Cultural Property (Fukuoka Prefecture Designation) === * Nakazato Fuji (Fujizuka): One of the larger mounds built by the Fuji-kō (a group of pilgrims to Mt. Fuji) from the Edo period to early Showa period. It stands 12 meters tall (from the base on its south side) with a diameter of 30 meters. A stone monument from Bunsei 5 (1822) indicates it existed during the Edo period. Among the 36 stone structures, the monument of the Dōso-gami is unique in the district. === Treasures === * Ema (votive plaques) commemorating the subjugation of the eight‐headed serpent (dating from Tenpō 5, January) * Ema commemorating Mt. Fuji ascents (dating from Keien 7, June) * Ema depicting the pilgrimage to Ise (by Fujigoro and Murata Masatarō, dating from Keien 3, March) == Access == * From the [[Seibu Ikebukuro Line]] at [[:en:Hōya Station|Hayamachi Station]] South Exit, take the {{ill|Midori Bus|ja|みどりバス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Midori Bus|qq=}} to “Bessobashi” (a 3‑minute walk from the bus stop)＜ref＞{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.nerima.tokyo.jp/kankomoyoshi/annai/rekishiwoshiru/rekishibunkazai/kakarikara/prnerima/dai30.pdf|title=Nerima Cultural Property No.30|publisher=City of Nerima|accessdate=2019-11-02|format=PDF}}＜/ref＞ * Or, from the [[Toei Oedo Line]] at [[:en:Hikarigaoka Station|Hikarigaoka Station]], take a bus for 19 minutes. == References ==
